WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.458 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:03.458 --> 00:00:17.882 align:middle line:90%


00:00:17.882 --> 00:00:19.590 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to Beyond Belief.

00:00:19.590 --> 00:00:21.840 align:middle line:84%
We have an amazing
program for you tonight.

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:24.900 align:middle line:84%
Jason Padgett with
us, a number theorist

00:00:24.900 --> 00:00:27.540 align:middle line:90%
with acquired Savant syndrome.

00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:32.130 align:middle line:84%
A traumatic brain injury changed
his life forever and made him

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:34.223 align:middle line:90%
a mathematical genius.

00:00:34.223 --> 00:00:36.390 align:middle line:84%
>>JASON PADGETT: Some people
would consider it that.

00:00:36.390 --> 00:00:37.860 align:middle line:90%
But for me, it's more--

00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:41.010 align:middle line:84%
it just makes the
mathematics behind motion

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:44.040 align:middle line:84%
and behind equations
much more easy to see.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:46.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Prior to
this injury, which

00:00:46.050 --> 00:00:48.030 align:middle line:84%
we'll get into in
a second, Jason,

00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:49.650 align:middle line:90%
you weren't that good with math?

00:00:49.650 --> 00:00:52.050 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: No, I had
basically a pre-algebra.

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:53.220 align:middle line:90%
I thought math was stupid.

00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:55.710 align:middle line:84%
I would literally say things
like, when are you going

00:00:55.710 --> 00:00:57.180 align:middle line:90%
to use that in the real world?

00:00:57.180 --> 00:01:00.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, after
the injury, how did you

00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:02.700 align:middle line:84%
know that your
mathematical skills had

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:04.410 align:middle line:90%
changed for the better?

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:06.090 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: So the
very first thing

00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:08.280 align:middle line:84%
that I noticed is that
when things moved instead

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:10.230 align:middle line:84%
of looking smooth
and continuous,

00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:12.120 align:middle line:90%
they were discrete and chunky.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:13.920 align:middle line:84%
So a good way to
think about it is

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:15.990 align:middle line:84%
like when you're
making a film, you're

00:01:15.990 --> 00:01:18.100 align:middle line:84%
taking individual
picture frames,

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:20.085 align:middle line:84%
and then you're
running them quickly.

00:01:20.085 --> 00:01:21.460 align:middle line:84%
And it makes it
look like motion.

00:01:21.460 --> 00:01:24.040 align:middle line:84%
Well, we construct a picture
the same way with our brains.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:26.740 align:middle line:84%
And it looks smooth
because one part

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:28.930 align:middle line:84%
of your brain, its
function is to smooth out

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:31.600 align:middle line:84%
the picture frames so that
they don't look jittery.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:33.460 align:middle line:84%
And that part of my
brain was affected.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:36.010 align:middle line:84%
And so when things move now,
I see the picture frames.

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:38.140 align:middle line:84%
But when you get into
physics and mathematics,

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.720 align:middle line:84%
you're literally just looking
at different time units,

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:42.550 align:middle line:84%
and getting those
units closer together

00:01:42.550 --> 00:01:45.700 align:middle line:84%
to get a better approximation
of what's occurring in reality.

00:01:45.700 --> 00:01:48.910 align:middle line:84%
So we're all doing calculus
and physics in the background,

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:50.620 align:middle line:90%
we're just not aware of it.

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:53.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Jason, explain to
us what Savant syndrome is?

00:01:53.590 --> 00:01:56.380 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: So Savant
syndrome is, many times,

00:01:56.380 --> 00:02:01.120 align:middle line:84%
it's people who excel in one
specific area or a tiny slice

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:01.990 align:middle line:90%
of an area.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:04.360 align:middle line:84%
And everything else is either
average or below average.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:08.169 align:middle line:84%
And for me, it's mathematical
skills, specifically

00:02:08.169 --> 00:02:09.580 align:middle line:90%
the geometry of math.

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:13.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So when those
skills aren't up to par,

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:16.150 align:middle line:90%
what's causing that?

00:02:16.150 --> 00:02:19.150 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: I mean, each person
has gifts in different areas,

00:02:19.150 --> 00:02:21.790 align:middle line:84%
depending on what part of your
brain has more connections

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:26.530 align:middle line:84%
and where those connections are
hooked to makes each person's

00:02:26.530 --> 00:02:28.240 align:middle line:90%
individual brain unique.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:30.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Synesthesia,
what is that?

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:32.260 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Synesthesia is
a blending of the senses

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:33.770 align:middle line:90%
like smelling a color.

00:02:33.770 --> 00:02:35.770 align:middle line:84%
People--somebody will say
that smells like blue.

00:02:35.770 --> 00:02:38.170 align:middle line:84%
The part of the brain
that is analyzing smell

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:41.788 align:middle line:84%
is somehow wired to the part of
the brain that analyzes sight.

00:02:41.788 --> 00:02:43.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Or I taste
red or something.

00:02:43.330 --> 00:02:43.990 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Exactly.

00:02:43.990 --> 00:02:44.710 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:46.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: This brain injury
you had, how old were you

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:47.740 align:middle line:90%
and what happened?

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:49.120 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: I was 32.

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:51.400 align:middle line:84%
And I had some friends
of mine had a few drinks

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:53.137 align:middle line:90%
at a bar, a little karaoke bar.

00:02:53.137 --> 00:02:55.720 align:middle line:84%
And they called me and asked if
I could give them a ride home.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:57.970 align:middle line:84%
So I went there, had
a Coke, sang a song.

00:02:57.970 --> 00:03:00.800 align:middle line:84%
As we left, these two guys
attacked me from behind they

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:01.600 align:middle line:90%
had been singing.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:02.560 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: For no reason?

00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:04.360 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: It turned out
they wanted my jacket.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:05.568 align:middle line:90%
At the time, we didn't know--

00:03:05.568 --> 00:03:07.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They
wanted your jacket?

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:07.920 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:12.430 align:middle line:84%
I had like a $99 Wilson's
cheap leather jacket on.

00:03:12.430 --> 00:03:14.142 align:middle line:90%
And that's what they wanted.

00:03:14.142 --> 00:03:15.850 align:middle line:84%
And so they ran up
behind me, one of them

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:18.220 align:middle line:84%
smashed me in the
back of the head.

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:19.640 align:middle line:90%
It was just a fist.

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:21.240 align:middle line:90%
But I didn't see it coming.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:26.460 align:middle line:84%
And so I felt this more--
almost heard this loud thump.

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:28.320 align:middle line:90%
And saw a flash of white light.

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:30.600 align:middle line:84%
And that flash that you
see is your brain bouncing

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:31.782 align:middle line:90%
on the inside of your skull.

00:03:31.782 --> 00:03:33.990 align:middle line:84%
And the next thing I knew
I was on the ground getting

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:35.100 align:middle line:90%
punched and kicked.

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:38.265 align:middle line:84%
And I remember thinking like
I'm going to die right now.

00:03:38.265 --> 00:03:40.620 align:middle line:84%
And that fight or
flight instinct came on.

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:43.290 align:middle line:84%
And I remember thinking I just
want to hurt one of these guys

00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:45.177 align:middle line:90%
before I die.

00:03:45.177 --> 00:03:47.760 align:middle line:84%
And I grabbed one of the guy's
legs because I was still dizzy.

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:50.460 align:middle line:84%
And I tried to bite him, but he
had these big baggy pants on.

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:51.870 align:middle line:90%
And I cracked my front teeth.

00:03:51.870 --> 00:03:52.897 align:middle line:90%
I bit down so hard.

00:03:52.897 --> 00:03:54.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did anybody
come to your aid?

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:55.280 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: No.

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:57.600 align:middle line:84%
There was two people watching,
and people were taking

00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:59.490 align:middle line:90%
pictures in the restaurant.

00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:01.920 align:middle line:84%
But one of the guys that
were watching, I looked up

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:02.910 align:middle line:90%
and I said help.

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:04.800 align:middle line:84%
And I ducked a punch
and I said help.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:06.390 align:middle line:84%
And he put his
hands up like this,

00:04:06.390 --> 00:04:07.830 align:middle line:90%
turned around, and walked away.

00:04:07.830 --> 00:04:09.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Like he didn't
want to get involved?

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:09.630 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:04:09.630 --> 00:04:11.100 align:middle line:84%
Making sure that
he was-- everybody

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:12.780 align:middle line:84%
knew he wasn't going
to get involved.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:14.880 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, I was
like, wow, I'm alone.

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:17.170 align:middle line:84%
And then finally at that,
we'd been fighting for maybe

00:04:17.170 --> 00:04:17.970 align:middle line:90%
like 30 seconds.

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:19.899 align:middle line:84%
And one of them said
give me your damn jacket.

00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:21.880 align:middle line:84%
And I literally just
took my jacket off,

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:23.260 align:middle line:90%
at that point was torn.

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:25.720 align:middle line:84%
And they grabbed
it and ran away.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:27.290 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 911 come?

00:04:27.290 --> 00:04:28.090 align:middle line:90%
The cops come?

00:04:28.090 --> 00:04:28.420 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:30.045 align:middle line:84%
Luckily, there was
a hospital literally

00:04:30.045 --> 00:04:31.750 align:middle line:90%
like 100 feet across the street.

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:33.835 align:middle line:90%
The cops came, did a report.

00:04:33.835 --> 00:04:35.710 align:middle line:84%
They sent me to the
hospital in an ambulance.

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And they diagnosed me with
a concussion and a bleeding

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:39.280 align:middle line:90%
kidney.

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:42.280 align:middle line:84%
And then a few hours later,
gave me a really strong pain

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:43.750 align:middle line:90%
medicine shot and sent me home.

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:46.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The guy must have
hit you, unfortunately,

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:47.420 align:middle line:90%
in the right spot?

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:48.220 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yes.

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:49.630 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it was right in
the back of the head.

00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:51.505 align:middle line:84%
And when you get hit in
the back of the head,

00:04:51.505 --> 00:04:54.760 align:middle line:84%
that tends to do
more damage to people

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.588 align:middle line:84%
than being hit in the
front of the head.

00:04:56.588 --> 00:04:57.880 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right above like the--

00:04:57.880 --> 00:04:59.200 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Right in the
back, right back here

00:04:59.200 --> 00:04:59.890 align:middle line:90%
behind this part.

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:01.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And you
felt it right away?

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:02.730 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah, it was weird.

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:04.780 align:middle line:84%
I heard it and saw it
more than I even felt it.

00:05:04.780 --> 00:05:05.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did you crack anything?

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:07.298 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: No, there
was no broken bones.

00:05:07.298 --> 00:05:10.180 align:middle line:84%
It was just the concussion
of my brain wiggling.

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:12.327 align:middle line:84%
And your brain hits the
front of your skull,

00:05:12.327 --> 00:05:14.410 align:middle line:84%
and then it does what's
called a contrecoup, where

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:15.785 align:middle line:84%
it whips back the
other direction

00:05:15.785 --> 00:05:17.560 align:middle line:90%
and hits the back of the skull.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:19.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You had a
brain scan, right?

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:20.350 align:middle line:90%
You flew to Finland.

00:05:20.350 --> 00:05:21.430 align:middle line:90%
Tell me about that.

00:05:21.430 --> 00:05:21.790 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:05:21.790 --> 00:05:24.010 align:middle line:84%
So in Finland, they have
something called a functional

00:05:24.010 --> 00:05:24.810 align:middle line:90%
MRI.

00:05:24.810 --> 00:05:27.168 align:middle line:84%
So regular MRIs will just
like you can see a tumor

00:05:27.168 --> 00:05:29.710 align:middle line:84%
or you can see the geometry of
what's going inside your head.

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:33.310 align:middle line:84%
A functional MRI has the
ability to somewhat map thought.

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:36.890 align:middle line:84%
So what it does is it shows how
much oxygen your brain is using

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:37.690 align:middle line:90%
and where.

00:05:37.690 --> 00:05:41.530 align:middle line:84%
So if, for instance, I were
to sit inside a functional MRI

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:43.238 align:middle line:84%
and I were to play
the piano, the part

00:05:43.238 --> 00:05:45.530 align:middle line:84%
of my brain that controls
playing the piano starts to--

00:05:45.530 --> 00:05:46.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Will be illuminated.

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:47.920 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Will be illuminated
because it works harder

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:49.670 align:middle line:84%
and it uses more oxygen.
And they can then

00:05:49.670 --> 00:05:51.940 align:middle line:84%
identify what part of my
brain is controlling that.

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:54.070 align:middle line:84%
So they had me sit in
the functional MRIs

00:05:54.070 --> 00:05:55.480 align:middle line:90%
and do mathematics.

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:59.290 align:middle line:84%
And they would look and see
what part of my brain worked,

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.150 align:middle line:84%
and then compare it
to control subjects.

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:02.710 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When did
you realize, Jason,

00:06:02.710 --> 00:06:05.722 align:middle line:84%
that this brain injury
gave you new abilities?

00:06:05.722 --> 00:06:07.180 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: The
first time I noticed

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:08.710 align:middle line:90%
anything was on the ride home.

00:06:08.710 --> 00:06:10.450 align:middle line:84%
But I think it was
the pain medicine.

00:06:10.450 --> 00:06:11.980 align:middle line:90%
Everything looked very strange.

00:06:11.980 --> 00:06:13.563 align:middle line:84%
But the pain medicine
was very strong.

00:06:13.563 --> 00:06:15.970 align:middle line:84%
But the next day, I
noticed it immediately.

00:06:15.970 --> 00:06:17.840 align:middle line:90%
I had vertigo really badly.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:20.600 align:middle line:84%
When I watched water go down
the drain, instead of looking

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:23.780 align:middle line:84%
smooth like it used to look,
it looked like little triangles

00:06:23.780 --> 00:06:26.900 align:middle line:84%
rotating or more like
even tangent lines

00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:30.290 align:middle line:84%
with triangles rotating and
getting smaller down the drain.

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:34.460 align:middle line:84%
And when a car would move, I
would see the picture frames.

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:36.835 align:middle line:84%
Instead of it looking smooth,
I would see picture frames.

00:06:36.835 --> 00:06:38.835 align:middle line:84%
But if a car was speeding
up, the picture frames

00:06:38.835 --> 00:06:39.860 align:middle line:90%
would get further apart.

00:06:39.860 --> 00:06:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And if it was slowing
down, the picture frames

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:42.710 align:middle line:90%
would get closer together.

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:45.920 align:middle line:84%
And the rate that
those distances changed

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:48.530 align:middle line:84%
was describing things like
velocity and acceleration.

00:06:48.530 --> 00:06:51.740 align:middle line:84%
But I didn't have mathematical
terms to describe it.

00:06:51.740 --> 00:06:53.600 align:middle line:84%
All I had at that
point was layman terms.

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:56.900 align:middle line:84%
So I started trying to
draw it, and I started

00:06:56.900 --> 00:06:58.340 align:middle line:90%
making up my own symbols.

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.500 align:middle line:84%
And eventually, I went back
to school and found out

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:01.790 align:middle line:90%
it was the exact same thing.

00:07:01.790 --> 00:07:04.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But you didn't know
at that point you had a--

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:05.210 align:middle line:90%
mathematical skills?

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:08.096 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: I knew
something was going on.

00:07:08.096 --> 00:07:11.840 align:middle line:84%
I worried, though,
that if I was having

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:13.430 align:middle line:90%
like delusions of grandeur.

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:15.830 align:middle line:84%
You see some guy who
is talking to himself,

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:17.210 align:middle line:90%
and you know he's crazy.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:19.180 align:middle line:84%
But I was like what
are the-- what's

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:20.560 align:middle line:90%
the odds of this happening?

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:22.960 align:middle line:84%
Me suddenly having
these revelations

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:24.940 align:middle line:90%
due to a head injury.

00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:27.490 align:middle line:84%
And so I would I would
go back and forth.

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:29.350 align:middle line:84%
But then when I would
sit down and logically

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:31.420 align:middle line:84%
go through the thought
process of what

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:33.880 align:middle line:84%
I was trying to describe,
it would make sense.

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:36.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did this injury
kind of change your perception

00:07:36.490 --> 00:07:37.930 align:middle line:90%
of the outside world?

00:07:37.930 --> 00:07:39.910 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: So the
main thing that it

00:07:39.910 --> 00:07:42.850 align:middle line:84%
changed was the seeing
the picture frames.

00:07:42.850 --> 00:07:44.470 align:middle line:84%
And so when things
move normally,

00:07:44.470 --> 00:07:45.580 align:middle line:90%
everything looks smooth.

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:49.100 align:middle line:84%
Now things always look
jittery and slightly pixelated

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:49.900 align:middle line:90%
around the edges.

00:07:49.900 --> 00:07:52.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So if you were looking
at me, I'd look jumpy to you?

00:07:52.360 --> 00:07:52.960 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Always.

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:53.760 align:middle line:90%
Always.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:56.350 align:middle line:84%
And if you're speeding
up, your picture frames

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:57.400 align:middle line:90%
get further apart.

00:07:57.400 --> 00:07:59.710 align:middle line:84%
And the rate that
those distances

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:01.270 align:middle line:84%
change between
the picture frames

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:03.640 align:middle line:84%
relative to the speed of
light is your velocity

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:04.690 align:middle line:90%
and acceleration.

00:08:04.690 --> 00:08:07.930 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would my voice stay
the same or would that go?

00:08:07.930 --> 00:08:08.800 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Nope.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:11.170 align:middle line:84%
I don't notice
anything with voices.

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:12.400 align:middle line:90%
Just visual.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:13.510 align:middle line:90%
It's all visual.

00:08:13.510 --> 00:08:14.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's amazing.

00:08:14.530 --> 00:08:16.450 align:middle line:84%
Did you think there was
something wrong with you?

00:08:16.450 --> 00:08:16.780 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:08:16.780 --> 00:08:17.860 align:middle line:84%
I knew there was
something wrong.

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:19.730 align:middle line:84%
I started getting
these muscle twitches

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:22.070 align:middle line:84%
and my muscles
would like vibrate

00:08:22.070 --> 00:08:24.095 align:middle line:84%
and it would happen
hundreds of times per day.

00:08:24.095 --> 00:08:25.220 align:middle line:90%
I started having headaches.

00:08:25.220 --> 00:08:27.613 align:middle line:84%
I had vertigo and
difficulty walking.

00:08:27.613 --> 00:08:29.030 align:middle line:84%
Instead of things--
it didn't just

00:08:29.030 --> 00:08:30.572 align:middle line:84%
look like things
would spin, it would

00:08:30.572 --> 00:08:32.360 align:middle line:90%
feel like they would spin.

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:34.760 align:middle line:84%
And it made it
difficult for my eyes

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:37.130 align:middle line:84%
to move smoothly
because everything

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:40.203 align:middle line:84%
looks jerky and discrete instead
of smooth and continuous.

00:08:40.203 --> 00:08:41.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How do you
see the world today?

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:42.590 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: The same way.

00:08:42.590 --> 00:08:44.240 align:middle line:84%
It just takes a while
to get used to it.

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:45.040 align:middle line:90%
And now--

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:46.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You accept it?

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:47.077 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Absolutely.

00:08:47.077 --> 00:08:48.320 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:50.450 align:middle line:84%
Even though there's
a bad side to it

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:53.280 align:middle line:84%
and there's been a lot of
medical issues from it,

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:54.390 align:middle line:90%
it's amazing.

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:59.790 align:middle line:84%
I wish everybody could see it
because I think everybody would

00:08:59.790 --> 00:09:02.970 align:middle line:84%
understand it because it's much
more intuitive than equations.

00:09:02.970 --> 00:09:05.820 align:middle line:84%
Equations are always
describing geometry.

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:08.940 align:middle line:84%
But geometry is more
natural for us to look at

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:11.160 align:middle line:84%
and to understand
than equations.

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:14.200 align:middle line:84%
And so I could
describe something,

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:17.670 align:middle line:84%
and we will later hear-- we'll
describe calculus 2, calculus 3

00:09:17.670 --> 00:09:20.460 align:middle line:84%
in terms that are so simple
that everybody will get it,

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:22.200 align:middle line:84%
but it's the exact
same thing as if you

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:23.280 align:middle line:90%
went to school for two years.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:25.440 align:middle line:84%
The only difference is is you
can't prove it with geometry,

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:26.970 align:middle line:90%
but you can still understand it.

00:09:26.970 --> 00:09:30.970 align:middle line:84%
Whereas mathematics allows
you to rigorously prove

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:31.770 align:middle line:90%
the theorems.

00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:33.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: At what
point, Jason, did

00:09:33.300 --> 00:09:37.050 align:middle line:90%
you realize I may be a Savant?

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:39.240 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: What
really, really hit me

00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:41.910 align:middle line:84%
that something big was
going on is one day,

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:44.250 align:middle line:84%
my daughter asked me how
the television worked,

00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:46.230 align:middle line:84%
because a commercial
for like Overstock.com

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:47.640 align:middle line:90%
came on and had a big circle.

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:49.080 align:middle line:84%
And she said how did
they make the picture

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:50.170 align:middle line:90%
work on the television screen?

00:09:50.170 --> 00:09:51.753 align:middle line:84%
And I said, Oh,
there's little pixels.

00:09:51.753 --> 00:09:53.967 align:middle line:84%
And as they change color,
that changes the picture.

00:09:53.967 --> 00:09:55.300 align:middle line:90%
And she goes, you're wrong, dad.

00:09:55.300 --> 00:09:56.320 align:middle line:84%
And I go what do
you mean I'm wrong?

00:09:56.320 --> 00:09:58.870 align:middle line:84%
And she goes, how do you make
a circle with rectangles?

00:09:58.870 --> 00:10:01.150 align:middle line:84%
And I was like wait
a second, you can't.

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:03.310 align:middle line:84%
I'm not looking at a
rectangle on that screen,

00:10:03.310 --> 00:10:04.780 align:middle line:90%
I'm looking at a zigzag.

00:10:04.780 --> 00:10:07.333 align:middle line:84%
It's just those pixels are
so tiny, it looks smooth.

00:10:07.333 --> 00:10:08.500 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It looks like that.

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:09.670 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: But I can
take those pixels

00:10:09.670 --> 00:10:11.140 align:middle line:84%
and cut them in
half to infinity,

00:10:11.140 --> 00:10:12.730 align:middle line:84%
and you never reach
a perfect circle.

00:10:12.730 --> 00:10:14.830 align:middle line:84%
You just approach closer
and closer forever.

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:17.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did you realize
there was a newer MRI

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:19.695 align:middle line:90%
machine available in Finland?

00:10:19.695 --> 00:10:21.820 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: With one of the
doctors that I spoke to,

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.153 align:middle line:84%
I remember speaking with Dr.
Treffert and another doctor

00:10:24.153 --> 00:10:25.330 align:middle line:90%
named Berit Brogaard.

00:10:25.330 --> 00:10:28.000 align:middle line:84%
And they started putting
me on to these places that

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:29.950 align:middle line:84%
were doing studies of
synesthesia and people

00:10:29.950 --> 00:10:30.850 align:middle line:90%
with Savant syndrome.

00:10:30.850 --> 00:10:32.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you flew
to Finland to find out

00:10:32.650 --> 00:10:34.610 align:middle line:84%
exactly how the injury
affected your brain?

00:10:34.610 --> 00:10:35.410 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yes.

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:37.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And turned
you into a savant.

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:38.220 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.155 align:middle line:90%
- It was an amazing experience.

00:10:40.155 --> 00:10:41.530 align:middle line:84%
There was a whole
bunch of images

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:45.790 align:middle line:84%
flashing in front of my eyes
that were mixed in together.

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:48.220 align:middle line:84%
Some were equations
that I would draw,

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:50.410 align:middle line:84%
all sorts of different
pictures that would flash.

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:52.330 align:middle line:90%
Some that were just mixed up.

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:54.070 align:middle line:90%
Some that were obvious fractals.

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:55.160 align:middle line:90%
Some that weren't.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:58.390 align:middle line:84%
The one that really stands out
was the one with little circles

00:10:58.390 --> 00:11:00.610 align:middle line:84%
that would expand and
get smaller, expand

00:11:00.610 --> 00:11:01.600 align:middle line:90%
and get smaller.

00:11:01.600 --> 00:11:04.510 align:middle line:84%
And eventually, it
would start to look

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:08.920 align:middle line:84%
like it was a right triangle
rotating with the little radius

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:11.830 align:middle line:84%
getting smaller and smaller and
smaller and larger and larger

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:13.120 align:middle line:90%
and larger.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:14.785 align:middle line:90%
But it was very intense.

00:11:14.785 --> 00:11:16.990 align:middle line:84%
After a while, it just
started to feel hypnotic.

00:11:16.990 --> 00:11:18.407 align:middle line:84%
- So basically
what's happening is

00:11:18.407 --> 00:11:20.620 align:middle line:84%
that there's electric
current, like electric circuit

00:11:20.620 --> 00:11:22.090 align:middle line:90%
inside the coil.

00:11:22.090 --> 00:11:25.570 align:middle line:84%
And that current creates
a magnetic field.

00:11:25.570 --> 00:11:29.650 align:middle line:84%
So when we place it
against your scalp,

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.560 align:middle line:84%
the magnetic field would
penetrate your skull,

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:35.410 align:middle line:84%
and it will stimulate
neurons in the brain.

00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:38.068 align:middle line:84%
