So normally like
even in, I think even

00:12:41.532 --> 00:12:43.990 align:middle line:84%
in language experiments, and
you see something in the right

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:44.790 align:middle line:90%
also.

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:46.842 align:middle line:84%
But it's so uniquely
in the left hemisphere.

00:12:46.842 --> 00:12:47.800 align:middle line:90%
[END OF VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:51.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So after this test,
what conclusions did they make?

00:12:51.430 --> 00:12:53.560 align:middle line:90%
What conclusions did you make?

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:55.270 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: So they
made a conclusion

00:12:55.270 --> 00:12:58.210 align:middle line:84%
that I had conscious
access to part of the brain

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:01.150 align:middle line:84%
that we normally don't
have conscious access to.

00:13:01.150 --> 00:13:04.360 align:middle line:84%
And I was told that
I had Savant syndrome

00:13:04.360 --> 00:13:06.640 align:middle line:90%
and a form of synesthesia.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:10.720 align:middle line:84%
For me specifically, it's
seeing numbers as shapes,

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:14.977 align:middle line:84%
because shapes are actually
the natural form of numbers.

00:13:14.977 --> 00:13:16.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And this is
still happening to you?

00:13:16.810 --> 00:13:17.610 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Always.

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:19.380 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I can't stop
thinking about it.

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:21.130 align:middle line:84%
I have I have difficulty
sleeping at night

00:13:21.130 --> 00:13:24.600 align:middle line:84%
because there's just
so much to think about,

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:25.600 align:middle line:90%
so much to wonder about.

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:31.450 align:middle line:84%
And the way that reality works
is so much more interesting

00:13:31.450 --> 00:13:35.000 align:middle line:84%
and intricate than what
I think most people would

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:35.800 align:middle line:90%
have imagined.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:37.342 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I notice
on the screen there

00:13:37.342 --> 00:13:40.090 align:middle line:90%
was MC square flashed up there.

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:41.480 align:middle line:90%
Einstein would be proud of you.

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:42.280 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:45.070 align:middle line:84%
So I have written that in a
slightly different way, which

00:13:45.070 --> 00:13:47.560 align:middle line:84%
is called Planck
constant times frequency

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:49.840 align:middle line:84%
equals mass times the
speed of light squared.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:51.792 align:middle line:84%
But it's still
describing energy.

00:13:51.792 --> 00:13:52.750 align:middle line:90%
They both equal energy.

00:13:52.750 --> 00:13:55.180 align:middle line:84%
But they describe energy
in different ways.

00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:57.340 align:middle line:84%
The Planck constant times
frequency describes it

00:13:57.340 --> 00:14:00.400 align:middle line:84%
in terms of frequency
and light, and mass times

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:04.240 align:middle line:84%
the speed of light squared
describes it in terms of mass.

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:07.630 align:middle line:84%
So one's quantum mechanics,
the other one's relativity.

00:14:07.630 --> 00:14:10.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If I told
you 284 times 20,

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:12.610 align:middle line:84%
would you instantly
know the answer?

00:14:12.610 --> 00:14:12.910 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: No.

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:13.630 align:middle line:90%
I don't do numbers.

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:14.950 align:middle line:90%
I'm sure I could figure it out.

00:14:14.950 --> 00:14:19.090 align:middle line:84%
I'd be like 1,000, I don't know,
be like 7,200 and something,

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:19.922 align:middle line:90%
280 I think.

00:14:19.922 --> 00:14:22.130 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But we'd all have
to think it out like that.

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:22.360 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Right.

00:14:22.360 --> 00:14:22.600 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:23.975 align:middle line:84%
But I still have
to think it out.

00:14:23.975 --> 00:14:26.530 align:middle line:84%
I don't-- like I don't do
like number calculations.

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:29.990 align:middle line:84%
It's specifically like
if I look at a shape,

00:14:29.990 --> 00:14:32.720 align:middle line:84%
I still have to sit down
and I can describe it

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:35.035 align:middle line:84%
to you in the exact
same way in layman terms

00:14:35.035 --> 00:14:36.410 align:middle line:84%
because when this
happened to me,

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:39.320 align:middle line:84%
I had to find a way to
describe it in normal terms.

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:43.100 align:middle line:84%
And so one day, I was actually
in the mall and I was drawing,

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:44.642 align:middle line:84%
and a physicist
happened to come by

00:14:44.642 --> 00:14:46.100 align:middle line:84%
and he asked me
what I was drawing.

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:47.630 align:middle line:84%
I said, well, I'm
trying to describe

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:50.300 align:middle line:84%
the discrete
structure of spacetime

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:51.620 align:middle line:90%
and the geometry of it.

00:14:51.620 --> 00:14:52.910 align:middle line:90%
And so we started talking.

00:14:52.910 --> 00:14:54.980 align:middle line:84%
And he said, you know,
it sounds like you're

00:14:54.980 --> 00:14:57.110 align:middle line:84%
trying to describe
unified field theory,

00:14:57.110 --> 00:14:58.940 align:middle line:84%
but you're doing
it in layman terms.

00:14:58.940 --> 00:15:00.740 align:middle line:84%
He said you have no
idea how weird that is.

00:15:00.740 --> 00:15:01.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because
you're not a scientist.

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:02.180 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Right.

00:15:02.180 --> 00:15:03.560 align:middle line:84%
And he said, have
you ever considered

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:04.520 align:middle line:90%
going back to school?

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:06.920 align:middle line:84%
And I was like, you know,
that's probably a good idea.

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:11.060 align:middle line:84%
And a week later, I went and
I enrolled in Math 99 Algebra.

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:13.880 align:middle line:84%
And the very first day of class,
my teacher graphed an equation,

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:16.170 align:middle line:84%
and I said you mean that
equation is that shape?

00:15:16.170 --> 00:15:16.970 align:middle line:90%
And she said yes.

00:15:16.970 --> 00:15:18.920 align:middle line:84%
And I said then we're
talking about the same thing,

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:20.180 align:middle line:90%
just in two different ways.

00:15:20.180 --> 00:15:21.647 align:middle line:90%
I'm drawing what it looks like.

00:15:21.647 --> 00:15:23.480 align:middle line:84%
You're writing an
equation that you can then

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:25.850 align:middle line:84%
graph what it looks like,
but they are identical.

00:15:25.850 --> 00:15:27.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Was it easy for you?

00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:29.360 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Much of
it was very easy.

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:33.710 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I thought that I came
in and I had pi drawn out.

00:15:33.710 --> 00:15:35.603 align:middle line:84%
And I had all these
drawings done.

00:15:35.603 --> 00:15:37.520 align:middle line:84%
And I thought I would
show them to a professor

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:38.810 align:middle line:84%
and they would say
that's the number pi.

00:15:38.810 --> 00:15:40.910 align:middle line:84%
And let me explain to
you how we calculate it.

00:15:40.910 --> 00:15:42.800 align:middle line:90%
And they would say what is that?

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:43.940 align:middle line:90%
It's a pretty picture.

00:15:43.940 --> 00:15:46.160 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't until I
got to like trigonometry

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:49.010 align:middle line:84%
and calculus that I could
write it in their terms.

00:15:49.010 --> 00:15:51.620 align:middle line:84%
And once I wrote it in
an equation and then put

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:53.660 align:middle line:84%
the drawing with it, then
they were like it's--

00:15:53.660 --> 00:15:55.790 align:middle line:84%
they would agree 100%,
they have to agree

00:15:55.790 --> 00:15:57.470 align:middle line:90%
because it is the same.

00:15:57.470 --> 00:16:00.890 align:middle line:84%
But it was interesting
seeing how they didn't see it

00:16:00.890 --> 00:16:04.010 align:middle line:84%
until I wrote it in the language
that they were taught to speak,

00:16:04.010 --> 00:16:05.240 align:middle line:90%
which is equations.

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:07.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What do you think
happened to your brain

00:16:07.970 --> 00:16:10.548 align:middle line:90%
to allow you to do this?

00:16:10.548 --> 00:16:11.840 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: I think we are all--

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:13.670 align:middle line:84%
in fact, I know we
are all doing it.

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:15.792 align:middle line:84%
So like if I throw a
ball to you, like we

00:16:15.792 --> 00:16:17.000 align:middle line:90%
don't think we're doing math.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:18.500 align:middle line:84%
But when I throw
that ball, you have

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:21.710 align:middle line:84%
to calculate the acceleration
of the ball due to gravity.

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:24.380 align:middle line:84%
The arc of the ball, the
three dimensional coordinates

00:16:24.380 --> 00:16:27.230 align:middle line:84%
of your hand and the ball,
the time lag from the nerves

00:16:27.230 --> 00:16:29.060 align:middle line:84%
to your fingers, yet
you just catch it.

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:31.477 align:middle line:84%
But if we were to try to grasp--
or to sit down and crunch

00:16:31.477 --> 00:16:33.140 align:middle line:84%
that equation, it
would take us hours,

00:16:33.140 --> 00:16:34.400 align:middle line:90%
yet you just catch the ball.

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:37.820 align:middle line:84%
So we're all doing
like estimated calculus

00:16:37.820 --> 00:16:39.320 align:middle line:84%
in the background,
even animals are.

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:41.060 align:middle line:84%
To be able to
navigate the world,

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:45.740 align:middle line:84%
you are defining velocity,
acceleration, probabilities.

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:47.418 align:middle line:84%
And you're doing it
in a general way.

00:16:47.418 --> 00:16:48.710 align:middle line:90%
It just runs in the background.

00:16:48.710 --> 00:16:49.850 align:middle line:90%
So we're not aware of it.

00:16:49.850 --> 00:16:53.000 align:middle line:84%
I think it's a it's a
function of evolution

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:57.200 align:middle line:84%
that it's so distracting
that it makes

00:16:57.200 --> 00:16:58.370 align:middle line:90%
you less likely to survive.

00:16:58.370 --> 00:17:00.537 align:middle line:84%
Like if this had happened
to me in the caveman days,

00:17:00.537 --> 00:17:02.900 align:middle line:84%
I would have been too busy
and distracted by everything

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:03.800 align:middle line:90%
that was going on around me.

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:05.480 align:middle line:84%
And I probably would have been
eaten by a lion or something.

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:07.105 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You would
have been considered

00:17:07.105 --> 00:17:10.040 align:middle line:84%
the Marconi of those days
