00:18:22.468 --> 00:18:24.760 align:middle line:84%
You can use this to describe
a lot of different things.

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:27.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Doesn't represent
the sun or anything like that?

00:18:27.070 --> 00:18:27.850 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Well, yeah.

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:30.400 align:middle line:84%
The sun-- when you see the sun
or you see any light source,

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:31.930 align:middle line:84%
it's going to look
just like that.

00:18:31.930 --> 00:18:36.280 align:middle line:84%
This also would represent
like gravitational lensing.

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:39.070 align:middle line:84%
Or when you see rings, if you
take a camera, a video camera

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:42.010 align:middle line:84%
and you point it at a light, you
start seeing these weird rings.

00:18:42.010 --> 00:18:44.890 align:middle line:84%
It's how the light refracts
at different angles.

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:47.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right, let's
look at your second photo.

00:18:47.890 --> 00:18:49.300 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: So this is--

00:18:49.300 --> 00:18:52.930 align:middle line:84%
yes, this is like the most
famous science experiment

00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:53.860 align:middle line:90%
probably in history.

00:18:53.860 --> 00:18:55.720 align:middle line:90%
It's the double slit experiment.

00:18:55.720 --> 00:19:01.240 align:middle line:84%
And it's how light, when you
shoot photons at two slits,

00:19:01.240 --> 00:19:03.580 align:middle line:84%
it will-- even if it
goes through one slit,

00:19:03.580 --> 00:19:06.340 align:middle line:84%
if you're not observing it, it
will interfere with itself as

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:08.170 align:middle line:90%
though it passed through both.

00:19:08.170 --> 00:19:12.730 align:middle line:84%
So this shows the wave particle
duality that light has.

00:19:12.730 --> 00:19:14.680 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you show
this to a mathematician,

00:19:14.680 --> 00:19:16.073 align:middle line:90%
