>>NOORY: Dr. Doll, why does
it take some kind of injury

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:47.960 align:middle line:84%
to the brain to push him into
that other level of being

00:24:47.960 --> 00:24:50.180 align:middle line:90%
a savant?

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:52.790 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: I think in
all of the stories

00:24:52.790 --> 00:24:56.240 align:middle line:84%
that we've had from different
kinds of experiences,

00:24:56.240 --> 00:24:58.730 align:middle line:84%
there's a process where
there's damage that occurs,

00:24:58.730 --> 00:25:02.780 align:middle line:84%
and then there's a recruitment
or an access to other skills

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:04.940 align:middle line:90%
or abilities that we may have.

00:25:04.940 --> 00:25:06.890 align:middle line:84%
It is very rare,
and we certainly

00:25:06.890 --> 00:25:09.200 align:middle line:84%
don't recommend anyone
harm their head in order

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:11.150 align:middle line:84%
to try to get
better at something.

00:25:11.150 --> 00:25:14.570 align:middle line:84%
But in these cases like
Jason, it is perception.

00:25:14.570 --> 00:25:16.680 align:middle line:84%
He's perceiving the
world differently.

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:19.440 align:middle line:84%
And what he describes
is sort of almost a look

00:25:19.440 --> 00:25:23.100 align:middle line:84%
behind the curtain on
how we track motion.

00:25:23.100 --> 00:25:26.130 align:middle line:84%
And how our brains
track motion actually

00:25:26.130 --> 00:25:29.730 align:middle line:84%
in his visual cortex where that
injury occurred has changed.

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:32.100 align:middle line:84%
And so now as a
form of synesthesia,

00:25:32.100 --> 00:25:34.890 align:middle line:84%
he's seeing the lines
as he describes pi

00:25:34.890 --> 00:25:36.900 align:middle line:90%
as a series of lines.

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:40.110 align:middle line:84%
And so that perceptional
change is really

00:25:40.110 --> 00:25:42.180 align:middle line:84%
where he's able to
understand and start

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:45.450 align:middle line:84%
to explain math in a very
unique and different way.

00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:46.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do we know
what will happen

00:25:46.950 --> 00:25:50.010 align:middle line:90%
in the future with Jason?

00:25:50.010 --> 00:25:51.420 align:middle line:90%
>>DOLL: You know what?

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:53.520 align:middle line:84%
Our years of working
with acquired Savant's,

00:25:53.520 --> 00:25:56.370 align:middle line:84%
one of the downsides
is oftentimes

00:25:56.370 --> 00:26:00.690 align:middle line:84%
a compulsion, that sense that
I have to do this new skill.

00:26:00.690 --> 00:26:05.580 align:middle line:84%
As that skill is practiced over
time, that pressure lessens.

00:26:05.580 --> 00:26:08.850 align:middle line:84%
And then people become
very attached, if you will,

00:26:08.850 --> 00:26:10.200 align:middle line:90%
to their skill.

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:12.540 align:middle line:84%
And there's concern that
it will fade over time.

00:26:12.540 --> 00:26:15.510 align:middle line:84%
And to our knowledge, those
skills do not fade over time.

00:26:15.510 --> 00:26:16.890 align:middle line:90%
But they do change.

00:26:16.890 --> 00:26:19.680 align:middle line:84%
And there's a
further exploration.

00:26:19.680 --> 00:26:21.390 align:middle line:90%
There's more comfort level.

00:26:21.390 --> 00:26:23.670 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully, some
of the negative side

00:26:23.670 --> 00:26:26.250 align:middle line:84%
effects of the injury
start to fade a little bit.

00:26:26.250 --> 00:26:29.160 align:middle line:84%
But as Jason says, he's
left with chronic headache

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:31.860 align:middle line:84%
and a variety of other things
that he struggles with yet.

00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:34.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The actor Dustin
Hoffman played in the movie

00:26:34.890 --> 00:26:38.400 align:middle line:84%
"Rain Man," which reminds
me a little bit of Jason.

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:41.310 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Treffert worked
with the real "Rain Man"

00:26:41.310 --> 00:26:44.340 align:middle line:84%
that Dustin Hoffman portrayed
in the movie "Rain Man."

00:26:44.340 --> 00:26:45.383 align:middle line:90%
What was that like?

00:26:45.383 --> 00:26:46.800 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: Well, for
Dr. Treffert, it

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:50.170 align:middle line:84%
was important to represent
these amazing minds

00:26:50.170 --> 00:26:53.920 align:middle line:84%
in the most accurate
and supportive way

00:26:53.920 --> 00:26:55.480 align:middle line:90%
of their unique abilities.

00:26:55.480 --> 00:26:59.740 align:middle line:84%
Kim Peek is a gentleman that
had absent corpus callosum.

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:02.650 align:middle line:84%
So he missed the connecting
tissue between his two brains.

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:06.220 align:middle line:84%
That actually allowed him
to read books with each eye

00:27:06.220 --> 00:27:08.350 align:middle line:90%
independently on each page.

00:27:08.350 --> 00:27:10.990 align:middle line:84%
And he had this incredible
memory for that.

00:27:10.990 --> 00:27:15.760 align:middle line:84%
And so he was considered the
human encyclopedia at the time.

00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:18.880 align:middle line:84%
But he also over the course of
time developed some insights

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:22.480 align:middle line:84%
and made some connections, and
was quite a remarkable thinker.

00:27:22.480 --> 00:27:25.780 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Treffert
really mirrored many

00:27:25.780 --> 00:27:28.090 align:middle line:84%
of the things he
recommended in the portrayal

00:27:28.090 --> 00:27:32.150 align:middle line:84%
that Dustin Hoffman had of the
savant on some other savants as

00:27:32.150 --> 00:27:32.950 align:middle line:90%
well.

00:27:32.950 --> 00:27:35.620 align:middle line:84%
Different skills and abilities
that they demonstrate too.

00:27:35.620 --> 00:27:37.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And Dr.
Doll, not everybody

00:27:37.120 --> 00:27:41.830 align:middle line:84%
who suffers brain trauma turns
out to be a savant, right?

00:27:41.830 --> 00:27:43.480 align:middle line:90%
>>DOLL: That's correct.

00:27:43.480 --> 00:27:46.360 align:middle line:84%
We're finding that there are
certain areas of the brain.

00:27:46.360 --> 00:27:50.290 align:middle line:84%
And typically, there's one
area on the left side that sort

00:27:50.290 --> 00:27:54.070 align:middle line:84%
of functions as a governor or
a control over your right side

00:27:54.070 --> 00:27:55.360 align:middle line:90%
of your brain.

00:27:55.360 --> 00:27:58.450 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Treffert would talk about
it as an injury that releases

00:27:58.450 --> 00:28:00.010 align:middle line:90%
the tyrant of your left brain.

00:28:00.010 --> 00:28:02.410 align:middle line:84%
So you can access
your right brain.

00:28:02.410 --> 00:28:06.160 align:middle line:84%
And that seems to be the most
consistent finding within

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:07.210 align:middle line:90%
Savant's.

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:10.120 align:middle line:84%
Congenital savants are
born with differences.

00:28:10.120 --> 00:28:12.100 align:middle line:84%
But oftentimes,
those skills do come

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:14.470 align:middle line:84%
from the wiring that
occurs that allows

00:28:14.470 --> 00:28:16.397 align:middle line:84%
them access to the right
side of their brains.

00:28:16.397 --> 00:28:17.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How much
of the brain have we

00:28:17.980 --> 00:28:20.800 align:middle line:90%
learned about by this time?

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:23.020 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: We're still
in the infancy stage.

00:28:23.020 --> 00:28:25.580 align:middle line:84%
There are some amazing
technologies that we've really

00:28:25.580 --> 00:28:26.380 align:middle line:90%
learned a lot.

00:28:26.380 --> 00:28:28.660 align:middle line:90%
We're starting to map networks.

00:28:28.660 --> 00:28:32.650 align:middle line:84%
And in some like diffuse
imaging technology,

00:28:32.650 --> 00:28:36.280 align:middle line:84%
it's really fascinating because
as Jason talks about the lines,

00:28:36.280 --> 00:28:39.100 align:middle line:84%
you actually see almost
these lines and patterns

00:28:39.100 --> 00:28:42.100 align:middle line:84%
in brain architecture
about the networks that

00:28:42.100 --> 00:28:44.770 align:middle line:90%
are connecting to each other.

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:48.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Elon Musk wants to put
a neuralink chip in our brains.

00:28:48.040 --> 00:28:52.220 align:middle line:90%
Will that help us or hurt us?

00:28:52.220 --> 00:28:55.700 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: I think that
technology is something that we

00:28:55.700 --> 00:28:57.650 align:middle line:90%
have to be very cautious about.

00:28:57.650 --> 00:28:59.660 align:middle line:84%
We have to understand
something thoroughly

00:28:59.660 --> 00:29:03.200 align:middle line:84%
before we start going
down those roads.

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:06.500 align:middle line:84%
It certainly would be appealing
to try to interface more

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:07.700 align:middle line:90%
with computers.

00:29:07.700 --> 00:29:09.440 align:middle line:84%
But I don't think
we even understand

00:29:09.440 --> 00:29:11.690 align:middle line:84%
what we're capable of when
we're still discovering

00:29:11.690 --> 00:29:14.900 align:middle line:84%
these amazing connections
and processes just

00:29:14.900 --> 00:29:17.840 align:middle line:84%
through the accidental
injuries that occur.

00:29:17.840 --> 00:29:21.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why do we need an
injury or some situation

00:29:21.260 --> 00:29:22.970 align:middle line:90%
in order to induce this?

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:26.110 align:middle line:90%
Why can't we do it without that?

00:29:26.110 --> 00:29:28.630 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: There has been, as
Jason mentioned, some technology

00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:32.620 align:middle line:84%
that pulses some
magnetic interference

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:34.510 align:middle line:84%
in different areas of
our brain, which allows

00:29:34.510 --> 00:29:36.190 align:middle line:90%
us to access other areas.

00:29:36.190 --> 00:29:37.930 align:middle line:84%
And we tend to think
of that especially

00:29:37.930 --> 00:29:40.360 align:middle line:90%
in our Western technology.

00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:42.370 align:middle line:84%
We're going to put
a helmet on instead

00:29:42.370 --> 00:29:45.610 align:middle line:84%
of learning to meditate,
for example, or practice

00:29:45.610 --> 00:29:46.750 align:middle line:90%
mindfulness.

00:29:46.750 --> 00:29:49.990 align:middle line:84%
We actually change our brain's
architecture when we meditate.

00:29:49.990 --> 00:29:52.030 align:middle line:84%
Six weeks of meditation
will actually

00:29:52.030 --> 00:29:53.350 align:middle line:90%
change your hypothalamus.

00:29:53.350 --> 00:29:55.420 align:middle line:84%
So we have more
control than we think

00:29:55.420 --> 00:29:59.140 align:middle line:84%
we do over accessing these
different skills and abilities.

00:29:59.140 --> 00:30:00.910 align:middle line:84%
It's through injury
that suddenly we

00:30:00.910 --> 00:30:03.190 align:middle line:84%
say, oh, I have
access or sometimes

00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:06.520 align:middle line:84%
disease process like
some forms of dementia.

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:08.980 align:middle line:84%
But it is also possible
that through more

00:30:08.980 --> 00:30:11.920 align:middle line:84%
intentional practice
and some techniques

00:30:11.920 --> 00:30:15.220 align:middle line:84%
that we can learn that we
can access all of our brains.

00:30:15.220 --> 00:30:17.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you still
working with Jason?

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:18.310 align:middle line:90%
>>DOLL: Yes.

00:30:18.310 --> 00:30:20.740 align:middle line:84%
We continue to be
in conversations.

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:23.170 align:middle line:84%
He's hopefully coming up and
visiting our newest place,

00:30:23.170 --> 00:30:26.570 align:middle line:84%
the Treffert Studios, so that
we can help him kind of put

00:30:26.570 --> 00:30:30.920 align:middle line:84%
together a visual representation
of how he perceives the world.

00:30:30.920 --> 00:30:34.340 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Jason, take a few
minutes and chat with Dr. Doll.

00:30:34.340 --> 00:30:36.057 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: How's it going?

00:30:36.057 --> 00:30:36.890 align:middle line:90%
>>DOLL: Really good.

00:30:36.890 --> 00:30:37.640 align:middle line:90%
How are you been doing?

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:38.060 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Good.

00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:39.727 align:middle line:84%
I'm looking forward
to coming out there.

00:30:39.727 --> 00:30:43.370 align:middle line:84%
We're going to be making
some videos of how--

00:30:43.370 --> 00:30:45.910 align:middle line:84%
what pi is describing
geometrically,

00:30:45.910 --> 00:30:48.410 align:middle line:84%
and they're going to be helping
me do some other things that

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:51.258 align:middle line:84%
have to do with the
holographic universe principle.

00:30:51.258 --> 00:30:53.300 align:middle line:84%
It's been really wonderful
working with you guys.

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:55.175 align:middle line:84%
You guys have changed
my life for the better.

00:30:55.175 --> 00:30:59.810 align:middle line:84%
And granted me a lot of
understanding of what

00:30:59.810 --> 00:31:04.730 align:middle line:84%
was going on, so that I didn't
feel quite so different, and so

00:31:04.730 --> 00:31:07.322 align:middle line:90%
out of place in the world.

00:31:07.322 --> 00:31:08.780 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: It's a real
rare condition.

00:31:08.780 --> 00:31:13.820 align:middle line:84%
And I think that while it's
a truly a gift to mathematics

00:31:13.820 --> 00:31:17.600 align:middle line:84%
and the things that you're
able to do, the story that--

00:31:17.600 --> 00:31:20.630 align:middle line:84%
and when asked like what is it
about Jason that's so amazing?

00:31:20.630 --> 00:31:23.840 align:middle line:84%
I also think that part of the
story, Jason, where you really

00:31:23.840 --> 00:31:26.210 align:middle line:84%
sought out those people
that harmed you and looked

00:31:26.210 --> 00:31:27.080 align:middle line:90%
to reconcile.

00:31:27.080 --> 00:31:29.810 align:middle line:84%
And I just think your
kindness and genuine nature

00:31:29.810 --> 00:31:31.720 align:middle line:90%
is also one of your superpowers.

00:31:31.720 --> 00:31:33.470 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: That was
one of the things that

00:31:33.470 --> 00:31:36.200 align:middle line:84%
was really amazing, is one
of my attackers reached out

00:31:36.200 --> 00:31:38.540 align:middle line:84%
to me about three
years ago and he

00:31:38.540 --> 00:31:40.820 align:middle line:90%
said he was watching a video.

00:31:40.820 --> 00:31:42.250 align:middle line:84%
And in the middle
of the video, he

00:31:42.250 --> 00:31:44.000 align:middle line:84%
said the video was
talking about these two

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:45.308 align:middle line:90%
guys that attacked somebody.

00:31:45.308 --> 00:31:46.850 align:middle line:84%
And he said halfway
through the show,

00:31:46.850 --> 00:31:49.010 align:middle line:90%
he realized he was the bad guy.

00:31:49.010 --> 00:31:52.250 align:middle line:84%
And he sent me a
text on Facebook

00:31:52.250 --> 00:31:54.980 align:middle line:84%
and said I just want to
let you know I apologize.

00:31:54.980 --> 00:32:00.127 align:middle line:84%
And he now sits on a national
nonprofit for at-risk youth

00:32:00.127 --> 00:32:01.460 align:middle line:90%
helping them change their lives.

00:32:01.460 --> 00:32:04.130 align:middle line:84%
So he is-- it turned out
that in the long run,

00:32:04.130 --> 00:32:06.110 align:middle line:84%
it turned out to be a
wonderful thing for me.

00:32:06.110 --> 00:32:07.730 align:middle line:84%
And in the long
run, it turned out

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:09.140 align:middle line:90%
it made his life better too.

00:32:09.140 --> 00:32:10.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you
get the jacket back?

00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:12.283 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Didn't
get the jacket back.

00:32:12.283 --> 00:32:13.310 align:middle line:90%
But that's OK.

00:32:13.310 --> 00:32:17.090 align:middle line:84%
But he did confirm that,
that was why they did it.

00:32:17.090 --> 00:32:19.190 align:middle line:84%
One of them said, Oh,
I like his jacket.

00:32:19.190 --> 00:32:21.260 align:middle line:84%
And the other guy said,
Oh, let's take it.

00:32:21.260 --> 00:32:23.480 align:middle line:84%
And they just-- they
had too much to drink.

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:25.700 align:middle line:90%
And they were young.

00:32:25.700 --> 00:32:28.820 align:middle line:84%
And had some bad
life experiences

00:32:28.820 --> 00:32:30.200 align:middle line:90%
that had just happened to them.

00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:32.510 align:middle line:84%
And when I look back
at it now, especially

00:32:32.510 --> 00:32:36.342 align:middle line:84%
after seeing how he
changed over the years,

00:32:36.342 --> 00:32:38.670 align:middle line:84%
I actually feel nothing
but compassion for him now.

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:39.470 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:32:39.470 --> 00:32:42.280 align:middle line:84%
The Treffert Center, how
has it changed your life?

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:44.030 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: It's changed
my life because it

00:32:44.030 --> 00:32:46.340 align:middle line:84%
brought a lot more understanding
to what was going on.

00:32:46.340 --> 00:32:51.110 align:middle line:84%
It helped to relieve some of
the fear and also some of that

00:32:51.110 --> 00:32:54.800 align:middle line:84%
worry that I had of what if
what if I'm the only one who

00:32:54.800 --> 00:32:56.900 align:middle line:90%
sees this and it's not real?

00:32:56.900 --> 00:32:58.910 align:middle line:84%
They helped with that,
and also going to school

00:32:58.910 --> 00:33:02.000 align:middle line:84%
helped with that so that I
was able to write it properly

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.330 align:middle line:84%
so that we knew for sure
that what I was doing

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:06.830 align:middle line:84%
was correct, because I would
doubt myselves at time-- myself

00:33:06.830 --> 00:33:10.790 align:middle line:84%
at times just thinking that
it was too good to be true.

00:33:10.790 --> 00:33:14.420 align:middle line:84%
It was too good to be
true, yet eventually

00:33:14.420 --> 00:33:16.340 align:middle line:84%
was able to show that
what I was drawing

00:33:16.340 --> 00:33:19.290 align:middle line:84%
was what I thought it was,
just a different way of looking

00:33:19.290 --> 00:33:20.090 align:middle line:90%
at it.

00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:22.550 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Dr. Doll, thank you
for being on Beyond Belief.

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:24.050 align:middle line:84%
>>DOLL: It's
absolutely my pleasure.

00:33:24.050 --> 00:33:26.060 align:middle line:84%
Thank you very
much for having me.

00:33:26.060 --> 00:33:28.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Jason, Dr. Doll
is a fascinating guy.

00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:30.260 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Yeah, he's
a very nice person.

00:33:30.260 --> 00:33:31.550 align:middle line:90%
They've changed my life.

00:33:31.550 --> 00:33:33.290 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How did you find them?

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:35.900 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Originally, I was
watching a television program,

00:33:35.900 --> 00:33:40.550 align:middle line:84%
and it was about a guy that was
talking about seeing numbers.

00:33:40.550 --> 00:33:42.260 align:middle line:84%
And that was the
first time I'd ever

00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:45.545 align:middle line:84%
heard anybody describe numbers
in a way that was visual.

00:33:45.545 --> 00:33:45.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That was
happening to you.

00:33:45.890 --> 00:33:46.700 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yes.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:49.760 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Treffert from
the Treffert Center who

00:33:49.760 --> 00:33:52.580 align:middle line:84%
works with Dr. Doll
was on the show,

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:54.860 align:middle line:84%
and I wound up emailing
them, and that's

00:33:54.860 --> 00:33:57.020 align:middle line:84%
how we came into
contact with each other.

00:33:57.020 --> 00:33:58.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Fascinating, it is.

00:33:58.400 --> 00:34:00.650 align:middle line:90%
What about the Doppler effect?

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:01.780 align:middle line:90%
Tell me about that.

00:34:01.780 --> 00:34:02.580 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:34:02.580 --> 00:34:04.730 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Yeah, the
Doppler effect is a good way

00:34:04.730 --> 00:34:07.070 align:middle line:84%
to describe relativity
so that everybody

00:34:07.070 --> 00:34:10.340 align:middle line:84%
can understand what
relativity is describing,

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:14.300 align:middle line:84%
and why we all have
our own unique reality.

00:34:14.300 --> 00:34:16.550 align:middle line:84%
So you know how you
hear a car drive by you

00:34:16.550 --> 00:34:19.400 align:middle line:84%
and it goes and
it changes pitch?

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:21.710 align:middle line:84%
So short wavelengths of
sound are a high pitch

00:34:21.710 --> 00:34:24.199 align:middle line:84%
and long wavelengths of
sound are a low pitch.

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:26.360 align:middle line:84%
As the car is moving
towards me, those waves

00:34:26.360 --> 00:34:28.110 align:middle line:84%
are squishing together
and getting closer.

00:34:28.110 --> 00:34:29.670 align:middle line:84%
And so you hear the
pitch getting higher,

00:34:29.670 --> 00:34:32.040 align:middle line:84%
then it goes [VOCALIZES] and
now it's moving away from me

00:34:32.040 --> 00:34:33.300 align:middle line:84%
and they stretch out
and they get longer

00:34:33.300 --> 00:34:34.530 align:middle line:84%
and you hear the
pitch getting lower.

00:34:34.530 --> 00:34:36.112 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Doppler
radar sort of thing.

00:34:36.112 --> 00:34:38.070 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: And so now we
add relativity to that

00:34:38.070 --> 00:34:40.920 align:middle line:84%
and we say the car is
driving from me towards you.

00:34:40.920 --> 00:34:42.570 align:middle line:84%
Well, since it's
moving away from me,

00:34:42.570 --> 00:34:44.070 align:middle line:84%
the waves are getting
longer for me.

00:34:44.070 --> 00:34:45.090 align:middle line:90%
So I hear a low pitch.

00:34:45.090 --> 00:34:47.628 align:middle line:84%
But relative to you,
it's moving towards you.

00:34:47.628 --> 00:34:49.920 align:middle line:84%
So the waves are compressing
and you hear a high pitch.

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:51.360 align:middle line:84%
And you stop right
there and say,

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:53.370 align:middle line:84%
is the sound that
the car is making

00:34:53.370 --> 00:34:54.960 align:middle line:90%
a low pitch or a high pitch?

00:34:54.960 --> 00:34:58.260 align:middle line:84%
It's making both sounds
relative to who's looking at it.

00:34:58.260 --> 00:35:00.660 align:middle line:84%
And then you imagine we have
an infinite number of people

00:35:00.660 --> 00:35:02.250 align:middle line:90%
all looking at that car.

00:35:02.250 --> 00:35:04.470 align:middle line:84%
And they're all moving
at different velocities.

00:35:04.470 --> 00:35:06.870 align:middle line:84%
Every single person will
measure a different wavelength

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:08.730 align:middle line:84%
and they'll all hear
a different sound,

00:35:08.730 --> 00:35:10.710 align:middle line:84%
yet everybody's
version of a reality

00:35:10.710 --> 00:35:12.720 align:middle line:84%
is correct, even though
they're all different.

00:35:12.720 --> 00:35:13.845 align:middle line:90%
And that applies to light--

00:35:13.845 --> 00:35:15.065 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How can that be?

00:35:15.065 --> 00:35:16.440 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: You
can take-- one way

00:35:16.440 --> 00:35:19.230 align:middle line:84%
that you can test it
is like take two guys

00:35:19.230 --> 00:35:21.990 align:middle line:84%
can go out with two cell phones
and have your buddy drive

00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:24.397 align:middle line:84%
his car in between you
while you film them.

00:35:24.397 --> 00:35:25.980 align:middle line:84%
And then play them
next to each other.

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:27.300 align:middle line:84%
And you'll hear the
high pitch on one,

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:28.425 align:middle line:90%
the low pitch on the other.

00:35:28.425 --> 00:35:31.800 align:middle line:84%
So where you are relative
to what you're observing

00:35:31.800 --> 00:35:33.258 align:middle line:90%
defines what it is.

00:35:33.258 --> 00:35:34.800 align:middle line:84%
But that doesn't
just apply to sound.

00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:37.080 align:middle line:84%
That applies to time,
that applies to light.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:38.310 align:middle line:90%
Everything about something.

00:35:38.310 --> 00:35:39.810 align:middle line:90%
You can change how big it is.

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:40.920 align:middle line:90%
Everything about it.

00:35:40.920 --> 00:35:43.650 align:middle line:84%
You can change by changing
your motion relative to it

00:35:43.650 --> 00:35:46.555 align:middle line:90%
and to you, that is reality.

00:35:46.555 --> 00:35:48.430 align:middle line:84%
But to somebody else in
a different position,

00:35:48.430 --> 00:35:50.760 align:middle line:84%
and a different velocity,
they have a slightly different

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:51.560 align:middle line:90%
picture.

00:35:51.560 --> 00:35:53.910 align:middle line:84%
But we all can agree
on reality around us

00:35:53.910 --> 00:35:56.130 align:middle line:84%
because we're all moving
generally the same speed.

00:35:56.130 --> 00:35:58.260 align:middle line:84%
But when you start approaching
the speed of light,

00:35:58.260 --> 00:35:59.580 align:middle line:90%
wild things happen.

00:35:59.580 --> 00:36:02.160 align:middle line:84%
And then you start having
vastly different experiences.

00:36:02.160 --> 00:36:05.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you understand any
of this prior to your injury?

00:36:05.490 --> 00:36:07.470 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: I thought
that I literally

00:36:07.470 --> 00:36:09.120 align:middle line:90%
would joke how math was stupid.

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:10.560 align:middle line:84%
And I would say
when are you going

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:12.058 align:middle line:90%
to use that in the real world?

00:36:12.058 --> 00:36:14.100 align:middle line:84%
And I remember thinking
that was so smart to say.

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:16.515 align:middle line:84%
And now I look back
at it and I can't even

00:36:16.515 --> 00:36:17.640 align:middle line:90%
believe I thought that way.

00:36:17.640 --> 00:36:19.710 align:middle line:90%
Math is everything.

00:36:19.710 --> 00:36:24.000 align:middle line:84%
There is nothing that is not
described by mathematics.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you in the
real world all the time?

00:36:26.910 --> 00:36:29.800 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Yeah, it depends on
what the real world is, right?

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:34.050 align:middle line:84%
I think about this over
and over like every person

00:36:34.050 --> 00:36:37.200 align:middle line:84%
has their own individual
version of reality.

00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:41.040 align:middle line:84%
And I try to think
in different ways

00:36:41.040 --> 00:36:45.930 align:middle line:84%
to help me understand some of
these principles differently.

00:36:45.930 --> 00:36:50.760 align:middle line:84%
Like I try to think in terms of
superposition or probability,

00:36:50.760 --> 00:36:54.150 align:middle line:84%
where you try to imagine
going from point A

00:36:54.150 --> 00:36:57.390 align:middle line:84%
to point B. What are all the
ways that I can go there?

00:36:57.390 --> 00:37:01.410 align:middle line:84%
And what is the average
sum of all of those ways?

00:37:01.410 --> 00:37:03.650 align:middle line:84%
And that describes what
actually happens in reality.

00:37:03.650 --> 00:37:06.150 align:middle line:84%
When it gets down into physics,
that's how they describe it.

00:37:06.150 --> 00:37:09.390 align:middle line:84%
We are the sum of
all possibilities.

00:37:09.390 --> 00:37:11.670 align:middle line:84%
And all of those
possibilities cancel out.

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:13.560 align:middle line:84%
And the one that
doesn't cancel out

00:37:13.560 --> 00:37:15.612 align:middle line:84%
is what happens almost
always in reality.

00:37:15.612 --> 00:37:17.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now how's
your health now?

00:37:17.070 --> 00:37:17.940 align:middle line:90%
You look good.

00:37:17.940 --> 00:37:18.990 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Yeah,
I'm feeling better.

00:37:18.990 --> 00:37:20.910 align:middle line:84%
I've actually-- when it
comes to like weight,

00:37:20.910 --> 00:37:21.710 align:middle line:90%
I'm feeling better.

00:37:21.710 --> 00:37:26.573 align:middle line:84%
When it comes to other
problems, they're pretty much

00:37:26.573 --> 00:37:27.990 align:middle line:84%
going to be there
for life when it

00:37:27.990 --> 00:37:30.480 align:middle line:84%
comes to like muscle twitches
and headaches and things

00:37:30.480 --> 00:37:31.280 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:34.590 align:middle line:84%
But I've learned to deal
with it better over time.

00:37:34.590 --> 00:37:36.210 align:middle line:90%
The OCD has gotten better.

00:37:36.210 --> 00:37:38.370 align:middle line:84%
I did this thing called
desensitization therapy.

00:37:38.370 --> 00:37:39.870 align:middle line:84%
I used to not be
able to open doors.

00:37:39.870 --> 00:37:41.400 align:middle line:84%
I would wait at
doors for somebody

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:42.780 align:middle line:84%
to open it because
I wouldn't touch it.

00:37:42.780 --> 00:37:43.665 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why?

00:37:43.665 --> 00:37:45.960 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Just because
you're suddenly aware--

00:37:45.960 --> 00:37:47.460 align:middle line:84%
being aware of
everything visually,

00:37:47.460 --> 00:37:49.650 align:middle line:84%
I would watch somebody watching
and then wipe their nose

00:37:49.650 --> 00:37:50.850 align:middle line:90%
and then grab the door handle.

00:37:50.850 --> 00:37:52.920 align:middle line:84%
And then I would see somebody
else do something similar, then

00:37:52.920 --> 00:37:55.470 align:middle line:84%
grab the door handle and I would
think I just don't want it--

00:37:55.470 --> 00:37:57.750 align:middle line:84%
it would almost
feel hot and sticky

00:37:57.750 --> 00:38:00.600 align:middle line:84%
just because I was so aware of
everything that was going on

00:38:00.600 --> 00:38:01.200 align:middle line:90%
that I didn't notice before.

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:01.860 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And it bugged you?

00:38:01.860 --> 00:38:03.027 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Oh, it was awful.

00:38:03.027 --> 00:38:04.470 align:middle line:90%
I would carry hand sanitizer.

00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:07.740 align:middle line:84%
When I went to school, I
would bleach off the tables.

00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:10.172 align:middle line:84%
I have a medical grade
UV light sanitizer--

00:38:10.172 --> 00:38:11.880 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were
pre-COVID, weren't you?

00:38:11.880 --> 00:38:12.030 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:12.990 align:middle line:90%
And this was pre-COVID.

00:38:12.990 --> 00:38:15.180 align:middle line:84%
Now people joke that I
was just ahead of COVID.

00:38:15.180 --> 00:38:15.930 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were
ahead of your time.

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:16.620 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Yeah.

00:38:16.620 --> 00:38:18.450 align:middle line:84%
Now everybody's starting
to feel something

00:38:18.450 --> 00:38:19.410 align:middle line:90%
similar to what I felt.

00:38:19.410 --> 00:38:21.077 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've got a
light bulb fixation.

00:38:21.077 --> 00:38:23.150 align:middle line:84%
If it's burned out, I
have to have it replaced.

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:23.950 align:middle line:90%
>>PADGETT: Right.

00:38:23.950 --> 00:38:24.750 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:38:24.750 --> 00:38:27.690 align:middle line:84%
And all those things are
different forms of compulsions

00:38:27.690 --> 00:38:29.637 align:middle line:90%
that we all feel.

00:38:29.637 --> 00:38:31.470 align:middle line:84%
And for me, it was just
getting to the point

00:38:31.470 --> 00:38:33.960 align:middle line:84%
where I was a little bit
more in control of them

00:38:33.960 --> 00:38:36.960 align:middle line:84%
instead of them being in control
of me, because a lot of times,

00:38:36.960 --> 00:38:38.790 align:middle line:84%
I would feel something--
like I wanted

00:38:38.790 --> 00:38:41.730 align:middle line:84%
to wash my hands constantly,
and I knew it was silly,

00:38:41.730 --> 00:38:44.070 align:middle line:84%
but I would still feel
the compulsion to do it.

00:38:44.070 --> 00:38:46.590 align:middle line:84%
And so what I did was
desensitization therapy,

00:38:46.590 --> 00:38:49.710 align:middle line:84%
where like we would clean a
doorknob with a bleach wipe.

00:38:49.710 --> 00:38:51.720 align:middle line:84%
And then I would make
myself touch the doorknob

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:53.610 align:middle line:84%
and touch my face because
I know it's clean.

00:38:53.610 --> 00:38:55.650 align:middle line:84%
And surprisingly, it
only takes a few days.

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:57.690 align:middle line:84%
So if there's anybody
that's suffering from OCD,

00:38:57.690 --> 00:38:58.950 align:middle line:90%
try that therapy.

00:38:58.950 --> 00:39:01.260 align:middle line:84%
You'd be surprised how
much it can help you.

00:39:01.260 --> 00:39:02.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What is the Bekenstein?

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:06.750 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: So the Bekenstein
bound is the number of ways

00:39:06.750 --> 00:39:10.020 align:middle line:84%
that our universe
can be reconfigured.

00:39:10.020 --> 00:39:12.240 align:middle line:84%
Imagine our universe,
and our universe

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:14.220 align:middle line:84%
is pixelated like a
television screen,

00:39:14.220 --> 00:39:16.170 align:middle line:84%
only the pixels are
very microscopic.

00:39:16.170 --> 00:39:19.140 align:middle line:84%
And the Bekenstein bound
asks, how many ways can we

00:39:19.140 --> 00:39:21.390 align:middle line:84%
rearrange the pixels
of our universe

00:39:21.390 --> 00:39:25.530 align:middle line:84%
to create a new and unique film
or a new and unique timeline?

00:39:25.530 --> 00:39:29.250 align:middle line:84%
And the number is 2 to the
10th to the 123rd power.

00:39:29.250 --> 00:39:31.230 align:middle line:84%
That's the number of
ways that our universe

00:39:31.230 --> 00:39:34.260 align:middle line:84%
can be reconfigured to
make a new timeline.

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:37.140 align:middle line:84%
But in that-- but if you
have that many big bangs,

00:39:37.140 --> 00:39:39.030 align:middle line:84%
then the pattern
repeats, or if you go out

00:39:39.030 --> 00:39:42.420 align:middle line:84%
that many observable sized
universes in our universe

00:39:42.420 --> 00:39:44.790 align:middle line:84%
now, if you just go out
forever, eventually,

00:39:44.790 --> 00:39:50.040 align:middle line:84%
2 to the 10th power to 123rd
universe is away from us,

00:39:50.040 --> 00:39:51.330 align:middle line:90%
the pattern will repeat also.

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:54.120 align:middle line:84%
So the Bekenstein bound is
just describing all the ways

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:56.670 align:middle line:84%
that our universe
can be reconfigured

00:39:56.670 --> 00:39:58.050 align:middle line:90%
to make a new and unique film.

00:39:58.050 --> 00:40:00.630 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You have a book
called "Struck by Genius."

00:40:00.630 --> 00:40:01.585 align:middle line:90%
Tell us about that.

00:40:01.585 --> 00:40:03.210 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Yeah, so
"Struck by Genius,"

00:40:03.210 --> 00:40:05.460 align:middle line:84%
I was lucky enough to
meet Maureen Seaberg.

00:40:05.460 --> 00:40:10.890 align:middle line:84%
She-- we met when I went to get
these scans done in Finland.

00:40:10.890 --> 00:40:12.480 align:middle line:90%
And she writes books.

00:40:12.480 --> 00:40:14.580 align:middle line:84%
And she wound up
writing the book for me.

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:16.350 align:middle line:90%
And she did a fantastic job.

00:40:16.350 --> 00:40:19.680 align:middle line:84%
And it was an option to be made
into a major motion picture.

00:40:19.680 --> 00:40:21.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There are
some people, Jason,

00:40:21.360 --> 00:40:24.480 align:middle line:84%
who believe we live in
a holographic universe.

00:40:24.480 --> 00:40:28.170 align:middle line:84%
What's your take on that
mathematically speaking?

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:30.870 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: I believe we do
live in a holographic universe.

00:40:30.870 --> 00:40:32.580 align:middle line:84%
So the holographic
universe principle

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:36.270 align:middle line:84%
is describing how our
reality is a projection,

00:40:36.270 --> 00:40:38.130 align:middle line:84%
like a hologram that
is projected onto what

00:40:38.130 --> 00:40:40.380 align:middle line:90%
we call 4D flat spacetime.

00:40:40.380 --> 00:40:42.480 align:middle line:84%
But it's projected
from black holes.

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:45.210 align:middle line:84%
But one of the problems
that we're having

00:40:45.210 --> 00:40:46.860 align:middle line:90%
is, where are the black holes?

00:40:46.860 --> 00:40:48.840 align:middle line:84%
And I think I have
a solution that

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:53.220 align:middle line:84%
may allow us to
understand where they are

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:54.390 align:middle line:90%
and why we don't see them.

00:40:54.390 --> 00:40:56.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You're talking
like a savant now.

00:40:56.670 --> 00:40:58.170 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: Well,
it's basically just

00:40:58.170 --> 00:41:00.870 align:middle line:84%
that black holes form
in between the picture

00:41:00.870 --> 00:41:01.963 align:middle line:90%
frames of our universe.

00:41:01.963 --> 00:41:03.630 align:middle line:84%
If you think of our
universe progressing

00:41:03.630 --> 00:41:06.480 align:middle line:84%
in time like a movie, in
between the picture frames when

00:41:06.480 --> 00:41:08.430 align:middle line:84%
you can't observe any
particles, they all

00:41:08.430 --> 00:41:09.840 align:middle line:90%
exist in superposition.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:13.560 align:middle line:84%
And wherever you have two
photons or the energy of two

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:16.710 align:middle line:84%
photons or more on one
pixel of our universe,

00:41:16.710 --> 00:41:18.630 align:middle line:84%
it will by definition
collapse into

00:41:18.630 --> 00:41:20.520 align:middle line:90%
a tiny microscopic black hole.

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:23.670 align:middle line:84%
And that black hole will
evaporate due to something

00:41:23.670 --> 00:41:25.140 align:middle line:90%
called Hawking radiation.

00:41:25.140 --> 00:41:28.070 align:middle line:84%
And that radiation
imparts a vector

00:41:28.070 --> 00:41:30.860 align:middle line:84%
onto the pixel, which then
describes the probability

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:32.330 align:middle line:90%
of the wave function collapse.

00:41:32.330 --> 00:41:33.997 align:middle line:84%
And so the only thing
that I'm coming up

00:41:33.997 --> 00:41:36.860 align:middle line:84%
with that is potentially
new is the reason

00:41:36.860 --> 00:41:38.990 align:middle line:84%
why we see the effects
of black holes,

00:41:38.990 --> 00:41:42.410 align:middle line:84%
but we don't see them is
because they form and evaporate.

00:41:42.410 --> 00:41:46.430 align:middle line:84%
What we perceive as
reality is the evaporation

00:41:46.430 --> 00:41:48.980 align:middle line:84%
of the black hole,
so that then reform

00:41:48.980 --> 00:41:50.960 align:middle line:84%
again in between the
next picture frames.

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:53.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How would you like
to be remembered, Jason?

00:41:53.870 --> 00:41:55.850 align:middle line:84%
>>PADGETT: I would
like to be remembered

00:41:55.850 --> 00:42:00.110 align:middle line:84%
in terms of helping people to
understand or raise awareness

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:03.470 align:middle line:84%
that all of us think
we don't like math.

00:42:03.470 --> 00:42:06.890 align:middle line:84%
And I understand the
courses are difficult.

00:42:06.890 --> 00:42:09.770 align:middle line:84%
And reading those books,
they can be monotonous.

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:12.320 align:middle line:84%
But if you do it the right
way, even if you just

00:42:12.320 --> 00:42:15.140 align:middle line:84%
want to understand it, if
you look at it geometrically,

00:42:15.140 --> 00:42:18.140 align:middle line:84%
I've talked to tens of thousands
of people over the years.

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:19.790 align:middle line:84%
And almost all of
them get nervous

00:42:19.790 --> 00:42:21.165 align:middle line:84%
when we start
talking about math.

00:42:21.165 --> 00:42:22.790 align:middle line:84%
But once we spend
5 or 10 minutes,

00:42:22.790 --> 00:42:25.340 align:middle line:84%
they're completely
engaged because everybody

00:42:25.340 --> 00:42:28.663 align:middle line:84%
can understand it if it's
shown to them the proper way.

00:42:28.663 --> 00:42:30.080 align:middle line:84%
And that's what I
would like to do

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:33.140 align:middle line:84%
is just show everybody
you can understand it.

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:35.243 align:middle line:84%
It's just it needs to
be in a language, which

00:42:35.243 --> 00:42:37.160 align:middle line:84%
is visual, which is how
we all live our lives.

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:38.835 align:middle line:84%
We don't live our
lives with equations.

